The error you are encountering is caused by the fact that the `model` variable does not live long enough to be used inside the `Arc::new(Mutex::new(model.meshes.iter().next().unwrap().clone()))` statement. The lifetime of `model.meshes` is bound to the `model` itself, which goes out of scope at the end of `main`.

To fix this, we need to ensure that the `model` lives long enough for the `mesh` to be valid or find a way to restructure the code such that the borrowed value does not outlive its parent.

Here's a possible solution to fix the issue:

1. Clone the necessary data from `model.meshes` before it's dropped.
2. Use this cloned data instead of borrowing from `model`.

Here is the modified code:

```rust
```rust
use std::sync::{Arc, Mutex};
use std::thread;
use nalgebra::Vector3;
use raylib::camera::Camera3D;
use raylib::drawing::RaylibDraw;
use raylib::init;
use raylib::prelude::{CameraMode, RaylibDraw3D, RaylibDrawHandle, RaylibMode3D, RaylibMode3DExt};
use crate::octree::{Octree, OctreeNode};

use rayon::prelude::*;
use crate::aabb::AABB;

mod loader;
mod octree;
mod vec_ops;
mod aabb;

fn draw_octree(d: &mut RaylibMode3D<RaylibDrawHandle>, node: &OctreeNode) {
    // draw only if leaf node
    if !node.faces.is_empty() {
        let size = node.aabb.size();
        d.draw_cube(
            raylib::prelude::Vector3::new(node.aabb.min.x, node.aabb.min.y, node.aabb.min.z),
            size.x, size.y, size.z,
            raylib::prelude::Color::new(0, 0, 255, 255),
        );
    }

    match node.children {
        Some(ref children) => {
            for child in children.iter() {
                draw_octree(d, &child);
            }
        }
        None => {}
    }
}

